<subSubSection id="0235936FC58E241800660F78A112F5CA" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="8586D1464805CA47FCC032AE86874DC2" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="177142E98D0A414136F8CA6E73CDD76A" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
The 
<taxonomicName id="AD00ADD961ABE2096CFA547B74159E92" genus="P." lsidName="P. perpusilla" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="perpusilla">
<emphasis id="B6ED2B9F06FE1F014957383601EE599F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. perpusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group includes at least seven closely related species in Europe, separable only by small details of male terminalia (
<bibRefCitation id="CDF08A55643BF8EEE088E69C7D27C2A7" author="Chandler, P" journalOrPublisher="Zapateri" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 24" refId="B6" refString="Chandler, P, Blasco-Zumeta, J, 2001. The fungus gnats (Diptera, Bolitophilidae, Keroplatidae and Mycetophilidae) of the Monegros Region (Zaragoza, Spain) and five other new European species of Pyratula Edwards and Sciophila Meigen. Zapateri 9: 1 - 24" title="The fungus gnats (Diptera, Bolitophilidae, Keroplatidae and Mycetophilidae) of the Monegros Region (Zaragoza, Spain) and five other new European species of Pyratula Edwards and Sciophila Meigen." volume="9" year="2001">Chandler and Blasco-Zumeta 2001</bibRefCitation>
). The studied Georgian specimens have the ventroapical margin of the gonocoxite with setose lobe (= without asetose protuberance) that is shared by three species, viz. 
<taxonomicName id="6854276B4DA7EBE2C7A60410BA31FBBA" genus="P." lsidName="P. perpusilla" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="perpusilla">
<emphasis id="33575948AD79573DB6E1E328B639D14A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. perpusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="468701EC440E6CD6966EA66D699010B4" genus="P." lsidName="P. alpicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="alpicola">
<emphasis id="BE0F0598707D212E476AB9C098510C89" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. alpicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Chandler, 2001 and 
<taxonomicName id="D0BC56A653F547E18D3D5659A95DC516" genus="P." lsidName="P. oracula" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="oracula">
<emphasis id="A19B4C7DFBB11C3105768A06E784F708" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. oracula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Chandler, 1994. The aedeagal complex is considerably short (elongate in 
<taxonomicName id="57CF08EC552421EABD47397DD962AB2A" genus="P." lsidName="P. oracula" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="oracula">
<emphasis id="0C8C0AE4D0D64D5A2A15CE3697BDBE28" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. oracula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the aedeagal sheath is interrupted medially on the ventral side (with complete bridge in 
<taxonomicName id="0386D082E8388DC978E5DA3FFAA67751" genus="P." lsidName="P. alpicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="alpicola">
<emphasis id="1F172F465ACA096C0E2BE3036F1D817C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. alpicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). However, the Georgian specimens are slightly different from 
<taxonomicName id="A1538E33D837C36C0C76EBF6581CBFD8" genus="P." lsidName="P. perpusilla" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="perpusilla">
<emphasis id="EB91BD0936D3D8BC7112A68E526D4B55" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. perpusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as figured by 
<bibRefCitation id="DFF884D58EF99822B83E1C60B290164B" author="Chandler, P" journalOrPublisher="Zapateri" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="1 - 24" refId="B6" refString="Chandler, P, Blasco-Zumeta, J, 2001. The fungus gnats (Diptera, Bolitophilidae, Keroplatidae and Mycetophilidae) of the Monegros Region (Zaragoza, Spain) and five other new European species of Pyratula Edwards and Sciophila Meigen. Zapateri 9: 1 - 24" title="The fungus gnats (Diptera, Bolitophilidae, Keroplatidae and Mycetophilidae) of the Monegros Region (Zaragoza, Spain) and five other new European species of Pyratula Edwards and Sciophila Meigen." volume="9" year="2001">Chandler and Blasco-Zumeta (2001</bibRefCitation>
: Figs 
<figureCitation id="FC15F56BAD2234049042B42D705669BC" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Habitus of Georgian fungus gnats of the families Bolitophilidae (A), Keroplatidae (B) and Mycetophilidae (C-I) A Bolitophila (Bolitophila) basicornis (Mayer, 1951) B Orfelia georgica Kurina &amp; Juergenstein, 2013 C Acnemia nitidicollis (Meigen, 1818) D Monoclona rufilatera (Walker, 1837) E Azana (Azana) anomala (Staeger, 1840) F Phthinia hyrcanica Zaitzev, 1984 G Neoempheria striata (Meigen, 1818) H Neoempheria brevilineata Okada, 1939 I Mycomya (Mycomya) marginata (Meigen, 1818)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1026.63749.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/524680" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">9</figureCitation>
- 
<figureCitation id="A789AF9521D559E77F6F66C5BAF8DCCF" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Habitus of Georgian fungus gnats of the family Mycetophilidae A Allodiopsis domestica (Meigen, 1830) B Rymosia affinis Winnertz, 1863 C Brevicornu griseicolle (Staeger, 1840) D Cordyla fissa Edwards, 1925 E Anatella longisetosa Dziedzicki, 1923 F Mycetophila magnicauda Strobl, 1895 G Epicypta scatophora (Perris, 1849) H Phronia tenuis Winnertz, 1863 I Sceptonia tenuis Edwards, 1925 J Zygomyia humeralis (Wiedemann, 1817) K Dynatosoma reciprocum (Walker, 1848)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1026.63749.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/524683" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">12</figureCitation>
) in having the distal dorsal corner of the aedeagal seath with a blunt protuberance that is otherwise typical to 
<taxonomicName id="186F11EE055256DDA7D896669AF65FC6" genus="P." lsidName="P. alpicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="alpicola">
<emphasis id="68D57F3D130CE054E52F159910250861" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. alpicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The material was compared to that of 
<taxonomicName id="1AC34C93B05571811468E2E8E10DC78A" genus="P." lsidName="P. alpicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="alpicola">
<emphasis id="F601B14A1D750A99C4715B3490331BB8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. alpicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="7AEC5153A83069E00D73FF87F4B33C3F" genus="P." lsidName="P. oracula" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="oracula">
<emphasis id="E9B2C6743517B750ED28379E22EE91A8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. oracula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from North 
<collectingCountry id="5ECF997E0773592BFBFF7ADC47765061" name="Italy">Italy</collectingCountry>
(cf. 
<bibRefCitation id="7DD2E52D000EEC8D1A0A19DF895E8402" author="Kurina, O" editor="Ziegler, J" journalOrPublisher="Supplements" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="245 - 293" refId="B28" refString="Kurina, O, 2008b. Sciaroidea excl. Sciaridae. In: Ziegler, J, Ed., Diptera Stelviana. A dipterological perspective on a changing alpine landscape (Vol. 1). Studia Dipterologica. Supplements 16: 245 - 293" title="Sciaroidea excl. Sciaridae." volume="16" volumeTitle="Diptera Stelviana. A dipterological perspective on a changing alpine landscape (Vol. 1). Studia Dipterologica." year="2008 b">Kurina 2008b</bibRefCitation>
) and, pending a further molecular study of this species-group, is considered to be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName id="6EAEFFF48C3ADD06E56C89D881F1151F" genus="P." lsidName="P. perpusilla" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="species" species="perpusilla">
<emphasis id="E891FD67A514FBF2011DD134D1A934FC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="69">P. perpusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
